args: Hanabusa never used to be a coward.
The weight of expectation ate away at\nhis heart—strong as it was—leaving the\nbroken man you see before you.
His technique, his youthful exuberance—\nI've never seen anything like it!
I've never seen someone so young with\nsuch talent. Sir, if I might be so bold...
You needn't even say it. Yes—he has the\npotential to be the pride of our family.

You will work and train harder than
anyone, Hanabusa, leaving a dazzling
mark upon the world of dance for
generations to come!
He was born a prodigy.\nHis talents seemed limitless.
His courage was one such virtue.\nEven learning the most daunting\nroutines never fazed him.
You would accuse Lady Mitsuhide of\nperjury?!
Whoa, take a breath, bud!\nNever said I didn't believe her!
I-I'm sorry... I'm just remembering all\nthe pressure.
So how'd our fearless prodigy here end\nup such a yellow-bellied puddin' cup?
They say that heaven is wont\nto challenge the strong.

In all things, Hanabusa displayed skill
and finesse. His family would push him
harder and harder, certain he could
surpass any limit.
But he was overexerting himself,\nand that began to eat away at him,\nuntil eventually...
Your next trial is to fulfill our family's\ngreatest ambition: performing the\noffering dance to Amaterasu.

Correct. To date, none have had this
unique honor. If you, in your youth,
were to be the first, your glory would
be written in the annals of history.
I trust I can count on you?
Mm? Afraid I couldn't hear you.
His spirit just...broke. He, who had never\nknown fear, found his heart ensnared by it.

In reality, it had been there all along.
But because he had been turning
a blind eye to it all his life, he
didn't know how to handle it.
Cripes... So that's how you ended up\nlike this?
Talk about boneheaded! Why'd you let it\nget that bad?!
If you were in that much pain, you shoulda\njust run away! It's okay fer kids to cry,\ny'know! Why didn't you?
Because suffering in silence is a virtue.\nIn Hinomoto, at least.
No matter how arduous a trial, it's seen as\nshameful to turn your back on it.
You do not complain. You silently do as\nyou are asked—and if failure means\ndeath, you welcome it.
That's the way we're taught to live.
This is especially true if you're born to a\nfamily of dancers. This is the fate of those\nborn in Hinomoto—no one can escape it.
That is just how it is.
That's crazy. But what about you,\nMitsuhide?
YOU sure don't come across that way.\nYer always sleepin'!
This was all brought on by my own\ninadequacy.
I should never have given up. If I had kept\npersevering, by now I would have—
That line of thinking is dangerous,\nyou know.
I'm sorry—I heard people talking from a\ndistance, and felt compelled to investigate.
I have to say—there's nothing to be gained\nfrom that line of thinking, Hanabusa.
Human beings are fallible. We can't go\nthrough life being so hard on ourselves.\nOtherwise, it's a fast-track to depression.
Is that so? I'm not much of an expert\nwhen it comes to handling emotions.
As long as I'm not overstepping, how\nabout I try looking after him for a while?
Ya think you can help him recover?
I am a nurse, after all. Perhaps I can help\nhim work through some of his feelings.
I can't turn my back on a person in need.\nI'm sure I can help, given enough time.
Fine by me. But I hope you know\nwhat you're getting yourself into.
I don't want to trouble you, though—\nUrgh... My stomach...
See? You really want to spend all day\nwith this guy? He's liable to ruin your\ndress.
Are you all right? Here, take some of this\nmedicine and give me some deep breaths.
Wait, maybe this'll work out! She's always\ngot stomach meds on her, and she knows\nhow to deal with people like him.
You got this, Aeleen! Help our boy\ngenius here get his groove back!
